var tafsirData_25 = {
  1: {
    "Blessed is the One Who sent down the Standard": "Allah, the Most High and Exalted, is the source of all blessings. He sent down the Quran, which is called 'Al-Furqan' (The Standard or The Criterion) because it distinguishes between truth and falsehood, right and wrong, guidance and misguidance. Just as a judge uses a standard to measure what is correct, the Quran serves as humanity's ultimate standard for distinguishing good from evil.",
    "to His servant": "This refers to Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). Allah honors him with the title 'servant' (abd), which is the highest honor a human can receive. Being a true servant of Allah means complete submission and devotion to Him. The Prophet received this revelation not because of wealth or status, but because of his sincere servitude to Allah.",
    "so that he may be a warner to the whole world": "The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was not sent for one tribe, one nation, or one time period. His message is universal, meant for all of humanity and jinn until the Day of Judgment. Unlike previous prophets who were sent to specific communities, Muhammad's mission encompasses every person who will ever live. This warning is an act of mercy—alerting people to the consequences of disbelief so they may change their ways before it is too late."
  },
  2: {
    "˹Allah is˺ the One to Whom belongs the kingdom of the heavens and the earth": "Allah alone owns and controls everything in existence—every galaxy, every star, every atom. Nothing happens without His permission. Kings and rulers of this world may claim authority over small portions of land, but Allah's dominion is absolute and eternal over all creation.",
    "Who has never had ˹any˺ offspring": "Allah has no children, sons, or daughters. He is not like His creation. He does not need offspring because He is eternal and self-sufficient. This directly addresses the false beliefs of those who claimed that Allah had children—whether the pagan Arabs who said angels were Allah's daughters, or Christians who called Jesus the son of God. Allah is far above such claims.",
    "nor does He have a partner in ˹governing˺ the kingdom": "Allah shares His authority with no one. There is no other god, no co-ruler, no helper that He depends upon. He alone decrees, creates, sustains, and governs all things. This is pure monotheism (Tawhid)—the foundation of Islamic belief.",
    "He has created everything, ordaining it precisely": "Allah created all things and determined their nature, function, lifespan, and destiny with perfect precision. Nothing is random or accidental. The sun rises and sets at exact times, the seasons change in order, and every creature has its sustenance measured. This shows Allah's infinite wisdom and knowledge. When you see how perfectly the human body functions or how ecosystems balance themselves, you witness this divine precision."
  },
  3: {
    "Yet they have taken besides Him gods who cannot create anything but are themselves created": "Despite knowing that Allah is the sole Creator and Sovereign, some people still choose to worship other beings or objects. These false gods cannot create even a fly or a grain of wheat. In fact, they themselves are created things—whether they are idols carved by human hands, or human beings elevated to divine status, or natural forces like the sun and moon. How illogical it is to worship something that was itself made! The one who carves an idol from wood or stone should realize that he is the creator of that idol, not the other way around.",
    "Nor can they protect or benefit themselves": "These false gods are completely powerless. They cannot even protect themselves from harm—an idol cannot stop someone from breaking it, a dead saint cannot prevent his grave from being desecrated. If they cannot help themselves, how could they possibly help those who worship them? This is a simple logical argument: why pray to something weaker than yourself?",
    "Nor can they control life, death, or resurrection": "The ultimate powers belong only to Allah: giving life, causing death, and resurrecting the dead for judgment. No idol, no human, no angel, no force of nature has any say in these matters. A doctor may treat illness, but only Allah decides who lives and who dies. This is why worship belongs to Allah alone—He alone holds the keys to existence itself."
  },
  4: {
    "The disbelievers say, \"This ˹Quran˺ is nothing but a fabrication which he made up with the help of others.\"": "The opponents of the Prophet accused him of inventing the Quran himself and claimed he had helpers who assisted him in composing it. Some said he learned from Jewish or Christian scholars, others pointed to foreign slaves who knew some scriptures. This accusation revealed their desperation—they could not explain how an unlettered man from the Arabian desert could produce such profound, eloquent, and consistent guidance, so they invented conspiracy theories.",
    "Their claim is totally unjustified and untrue!": "Allah declares their accusation to be a complete lie and an act of injustice. It is unjustified because there is no evidence for it—the Prophet was known for his honesty throughout his life, earning the title 'Al-Amin' (The Trustworthy) even before prophethood. It is untrue because the Quran's miraculous nature, its consistency over 23 years of revelation, and its perfect preservation prove it could only come from Allah. They accused an innocent man of the gravest lie, and this itself is a great sin."
  },
  5: {
    "And they say, \"˹These revelations are only˺ ancient fables which he has had written down": "Another accusation was that the Quran contained nothing new—just old stories and myths from previous civilizations that Muhammad collected and compiled. They claimed he had scribes write these tales down for him. This ignored the fact that the Prophet could neither read nor write, and that the Quran contains knowledge that no human of that time could have known, including details about embryology, the universe, and historical events that were lost to the Arabs.",
    "and they are rehearsed to him morning and evening.\"": "They claimed someone was teaching these stories to Muhammad regularly, morning and evening, and he would then recite them to people as if they were divine revelation. This accusation was absurd because the Prophet's life was public—his companions were with him constantly, and no such secret teaching sessions ever occurred. Moreover, whoever this supposed teacher was should have been identified, yet no one could name such a person with any credibility."
  },
  6: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"This ˹Quran˺ has been revealed by the One Who knows the secrets of the heavens and the earth.": "Allah commands the Prophet to respond to these false accusations with a powerful statement: the Quran comes from the One who knows every hidden thing in creation. Allah knows the secrets of the heavens—the movements of stars, the nature of angels, events before time began. He knows the secrets of the earth—what lies beneath the oceans, inside mountains, and within the hearts of people. A book containing such profound truths about the unseen could only come from the All-Knowing Creator.",
    "Surely He is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.\"": "Despite the terrible accusations and disbelief of these people, Allah reminds them of His forgiveness and mercy. This is an invitation—even after such grave sins as denying Allah's Book and slandering His Prophet, the door of repentance remains open. If they turn back to Allah sincerely, He will forgive them. This shows that the Quran's message is not about revenge but about guidance and mercy."
  },
  7: {
    "And they say ˹mockingly˺, \"What kind of messenger is this who eats food and goes about in market-places ˹for a living˺?": "The disbelievers mocked the Prophet because he was a normal human being. He ate food like everyone else, he walked in the marketplaces buying and selling, he experienced hunger and tiredness. They expected a messenger from God to be some supernatural being who did not have human needs. But this was their misunderstanding—prophets were always human so that people could relate to them, learn from them, and follow their example. If an angel came as a messenger, humans could say, \"He doesn't understand our struggles.\" The Prophet's humanity was a mercy, not a weakness.",
    "If only an angel had been sent down with him to be his co-warner": "They demanded that an angel accompany the Prophet visibly, confirming his message. They thought this would make the message more believable. But Allah's wisdom dictated otherwise—faith requires accepting the unseen based on evidence and reason, not being forced to believe by overwhelming supernatural displays. Moreover, if angels appeared to them in their true form, they would be terrified and destroyed, and they would have no time left for repentance."
  },
  8: {
    "or a treasure had been cast down to him": "They also demanded that if Muhammad was truly a prophet, he should be showered with wealth from the sky. In their worldly thinking, a true representative of God should be rich and powerful. But prophethood was never about material wealth—it was about spiritual guidance. The Prophet lived simply, sometimes going days without proper food, tying stones to his stomach from hunger. His poverty was a proof of his sincerity, not a mark against him.",
    "or he had had a garden from which he may eat!": "Similarly, they mocked that he should at least have a private garden that miraculously produced food for him, showing divine favor. Again, they measured everything by worldly standards. They failed to see that the Prophet's message, his character, and the Quran itself were greater signs than any garden or treasure could ever be.",
    "And the wrongdoers say ˹to the believers˺, \"You are only following a bewitched man.\"": "When they could not discredit the message, they attacked the messenger personally. They told the believers that Muhammad was under a magic spell, that he was deluded or mentally affected. This was a desperate attempt to turn people away from him. But the Prophet's clarity of mind, his wisdom, his consistency, and his noble character were obvious to anyone who spent time with him. Even his enemies trusted him with their valuables because they knew his honesty."
  },
  9: {
    "See ˹O Prophet˺ how they call you names!": "Allah draws the Prophet's attention to the various insults and labels thrown at him—liar, magician, madman, poet, bewitched person. They could not settle on one accusation because none of them fit. Their contradictory claims exposed their confusion and desperation. One day he was a clever fabricator, another day he was a confused madman—which was it? The inconsistency showed they had no real argument.",
    "So they have gone so ˹far˺ astray that they cannot find the ˹Right˺ Way.": "Because of their arrogance and refusal to accept truth, they became completely lost. They were so deep in their misguidance that they could not find their way back to the straight path. This is a warning: when a person persistently rejects truth and invents excuses, their heart becomes sealed, and they lose the ability to recognize guidance even when it is right in front of them."
  },
  10: {
    "Blessed is the One Who—if He wills—can give you far better than ˹all˺ that": "Allah responds to their materialistic demands by affirming His unlimited power. If Allah wanted, He could give the Prophet more wealth and splendor than the disbelievers could imagine. It was not inability that kept the Prophet in simplicity—it was divine wisdom. The Prophet's simple life demonstrated that this world's pleasures are not the goal; the Hereafter is.",
    "gardens under which rivers flow, and palaces as well": "Allah could grant the Prophet magnificent gardens with flowing rivers and grand palaces in this world. But the Prophet's mission was not about worldly luxury. He was offered the treasures of the earth and chose instead to be a humble servant-prophet who would be hungry one day and full the next, always grateful to Allah. The real gardens and palaces are reserved for him and the believers in Paradise—eternal and far greater than anything this temporary world could offer."
  },
  11: {
    "In fact, they deny the Hour.": "The root of their problem is deeper than their objections about the Prophet eating food or not having treasures. Their real problem is that they deny the Day of Judgment. They do not believe they will stand before Allah and be held accountable for their deeds. When a person denies the Hereafter, they lose motivation to follow guidance—why sacrifice worldly pleasures if there is no reward? Why avoid sins if there is no punishment? This denial is the foundation of their disbelief.",
    "And for the deniers of the Hour, We have prepared a blazing Fire.": "Allah has already prepared punishment for those who reject the Day of Judgment. The word 'prepared' indicates that Hell is not something that will be created later—it exists now, waiting for its inhabitants. This is a serious warning: the consequences of denying the Hereafter are not theoretical; they are real and prepared."
  },
  12: {
    "Once it sees them from a distance": "Hell is described as if it has awareness—it sees its inhabitants approaching. Some scholars understand this literally, that Allah gives Hell the ability to perceive. Others see it as a vivid description of how close and real the punishment is. Either way, the image is terrifying: before they even reach Hell, it has already spotted them like a predator seeing its prey.",
    "they will hear it fuming and growling.": "From far away, the people of Hell will hear its terrifying sounds—the raging, bubbling fury of the Fire, like an angry beast growling before it attacks. These sounds will fill them with terror before they even enter. The Hellfire is not just a physical punishment; the psychological horror of hearing its rage will be part of their torment."
  },
  13: {
    "And when they are tossed into a narrow place inside ˹Hell˺, chained together": "They will not enter Hell with any dignity—they will be thrown in like worthless objects. The place will be extremely narrow and cramped, adding to their distress. They will be bound in chains, unable to move or escape. Imagine being packed tightly with others, unable to stretch, surrounded by fire, and chained so you cannot even try to flee. This is the opposite of the spacious Paradise promised to believers.",
    "then and there they will cry out for ˹instant˺ destruction.": "In that moment of unbearable suffering, they will wish for total annihilation. They will cry out for death, for non-existence, for anything to end their torment. But in the Hereafter, death does not exist. They will remain in that punishment, unable to die, unable to escape."
  },
  14: {
    "˹They will be told,˺ \"Do not cry only once for destruction, but cry many times over!\"": "This is a devastating response to their cries for death. They will be told mockingly that one cry is not enough—their suffering is so great and so endless that they should cry out for destruction again and again, knowing it will never come. This emphasizes the eternity and severity of their punishment. No relief, no end, no escape—only endless regret and torment."
  },
  15: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"Is this better or the Garden of Eternity which the righteous have been promised": "Allah commands the Prophet to pose this question: compare the terrible fate of the disbelievers with what awaits the righteous. Is the blazing Fire better, or the eternal Garden of Paradise? The answer is obvious, yet people still choose paths that lead to punishment over paths that lead to reward. The 'righteous' (muttaqoon) are those who are conscious of Allah, who fear His displeasure and hope for His mercy, and who act accordingly.",
    "as a reward and ˹an ultimate˺ destination?": "Paradise is both a reward for good deeds and the final home of the believers. It is not a temporary visit but an eternal dwelling. Everything the righteous did in this world—their prayers, their patience, their charity, their struggles—leads to this beautiful destination. While the disbelievers mocked the Prophet for not having gardens in this world, the believers are promised gardens in the Hereafter that will never end."
  },
  16: {
    "There they will have whatever they wish for, forever.": "In Paradise, the believers will have everything they desire. There will be no unfulfilled wishes, no longing, no \"if only.\" Whatever the heart desires—food, drink, companionship, beauty, peace—will be available instantly. And unlike worldly pleasures that fade, these blessings are eternal. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described that in Paradise there are things no eye has seen, no ear has heard, and no human heart has imagined.",
    "That is a promise ˹to be sought after˺, binding on your Lord.\"": "This promise of Paradise is not uncertain—it is guaranteed by Allah, and He never breaks His promises. The believers can request this promise, hold Allah to it, because He Himself has made it binding upon Himself out of His mercy. When Allah promises something, it will absolutely happen. This should give believers confidence and motivation to strive for Paradise, knowing that their Lord's word is certain."
  },
  17: {
    "˹Watch for˺ the Day He will gather them along with what they used to worship besides Allah": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will gather the polytheists together with everything they worshipped—whether idols, angels, prophets, saints, or any other beings they took as gods besides Allah. This gathering is for confrontation and accountability. The objects of worship will be brought as witnesses against their worshippers.",
    "and ask ˹the objects of worship˺, \"Was it you who misled these servants of Mine, or did they stray from the Way ˹on their own˺?\"": "Allah will question these false gods directly: did you tell these people to worship you? Did you lead them astray? Or did they go astray by themselves? This question is not because Allah does not know the answer—He knows everything. Rather, it is to establish proof and humiliate the polytheists in front of everyone, showing that their gods will not support them."
  },
  18: {
    "They will say, \"Glory be to You! It was not right for ˹others like˺ us to take any lords besides You": "The beings that were worshipped will immediately declare Allah's perfection and distance themselves from any blame. They will say: we ourselves are servants of Allah; how could we ask others to worship us? We never claimed divinity. This includes Jesus, the angels, and righteous people who were wrongly worshipped. They will all declare their innocence and their own servitude to Allah.",
    "but You allowed enjoyment for them and their forefathers ˹for so long˺ that they forgot ˹Your˺ remembrance": "The false gods will explain that these people and their ancestors were given long lives and worldly comforts by Allah as a test. Instead of being grateful and remembering Allah, they became distracted by these blessings and forgot about their Creator. They became so absorbed in worldly pleasures that they neglected worship and guidance.",
    "and became a doomed people.\"": "Because of their forgetfulness and neglect of Allah's remembrance, they became a destroyed, ruined people. They wasted their chance at salvation. The word 'boor' means a people who are ruined, destroyed, and have no good in them. Their own choices led them to this destruction."
  },
  19: {
    "˹The doomed will be told˺, \"Your gods have clearly denied your claims.": "The polytheists will be told directly: those beings you worshipped have just contradicted everything you believed. They denied that they ever asked to be worshipped or that they could help you. All your claims about them being gods or intercessors were false, and now they themselves have testified against you.",
    "So now you can neither ward off ˹the punishment˺ nor get any help.\"": "At this point, there is no escape. They cannot turn away the punishment that is coming, and no one will help them—not their false gods, not their wealth, not their ancestors. They are utterly alone and helpless before Allah's judgment.",
    "And whoever of you does wrong, We will make them taste a horrible punishment.": "This is a general warning to all people: anyone who commits shirk (associating partners with Allah) or other major wrongs will face severe punishment. This applies not only to the ancient polytheists but to anyone in any time who commits the same crimes. The punishment is described as 'great' to emphasize its severity."
  },
  20: {
    "We never sent any messenger before you ˹O Prophet˺, who did not eat food and go about in market-places.": "Allah consoles the Prophet and establishes a universal principle: every prophet before Muhammad also ate food and walked in marketplaces. Moses, Abraham, Jesus, Noah—all of them were human beings with human needs. They were not angels or supernatural beings. This refutes the objection raised by the Quraysh. The prophets' humanity was essential so that people could follow their example. An angel-messenger would be impossible for humans to imitate.",
    "We have made some of you a trial for others.": "Allah tests people through one another. The rich are tested by the poor, the healthy by the sick, the powerful by the weak. The disbelievers were tested by having to follow a prophet who was not wealthy or powerful by worldly standards. Would they accept truth based on its merit, or would they reject it because the messenger did not meet their material expectations? Similarly, the Prophet was tested by having to endure the mockery and rejection of his people.",
    "Will you ˹not then˺ be patient?": "Allah asks: knowing that this life is a test, will you exercise patience? Patience is the key to passing life's trials. The Prophet showed immense patience despite all the insults and accusations. Believers are called to do the same—to endure hardships with faith, knowing that Allah sees everything and will reward patience.",
    "And your Lord is All-Seeing.": "Nothing escapes Allah's observation. He sees the patience of the believers, He sees the mockery of the disbelievers, He sees every struggle and every act of worship. This should comfort the believers—their efforts are not unnoticed. And it should warn the wrongdoers—their crimes are fully witnessed by the One who will judge them."
  },
  21: {
    "Those who do not expect to meet Us say, \"If only the angels were sent down to us, or we could see our Lord!\"": "Those who deny the Day of Judgment make arrogant demands: they want to see angels descending, or they want to see Allah Himself directly. They consider themselves so important that the usual means of guidance are not good enough for them. They want personal, extraordinary signs before they will believe. This attitude shows their lack of humility and their denial of meeting Allah in the Hereafter.",
    "They have certainly been carried away by their arrogance": "Their demand stems from pride, not sincere seeking of truth. They think they are too important to simply accept the message brought by a human messenger. They want special treatment. This arrogance blinds them to the signs that are already abundant around them.",
    "and have entirely exceeded all limits.": "Their arrogance is not minor—they have transgressed all boundaries of proper behavior toward Allah. To demand to see the Creator of the universe as a condition for belief is the height of insolence. They fail to recognize their own insignificance before the Almighty."
  },
  22: {
    "˹But˺ on the Day they will see the angels, there will be no good news for the wicked": "They asked to see angels, but be careful what you wish for. The disbelievers will indeed see angels—on the Day of Judgment. But when that happens, it will not be a happy occasion for them. The angels will not bring them glad tidings of paradise; instead, they will bring punishment. For the believers, seeing angels is a moment of joy; for the criminals, it is the beginning of their eternal doom.",
    "who will cry, \"Keep away! Away ˹from us˺!\"": "Some scholars interpret this as the disbelievers crying out, wishing the angels would stay away from them. Others interpret it as the angels themselves saying to the disbelievers, \"Paradise is forbidden for you!\" Either way, the meaning is that the disbelievers will find no mercy on that Day. Everything good will be kept away from them. The word 'hijran mahjura' conveys a complete barrier between them and any good."
  },
  23: {
    "Then We will turn to whatever ˹good˺ deeds they did, reducing them to scattered dust.": "Any good deeds the disbelievers may have done in this world—charity, kindness, helping others—will be examined by Allah and rendered worthless. Because their deeds were not based on faith in Allah and the Last Day, they will be like dust particles floating in the air, scattered and meaningless. Good deeds without correct belief are like a building without foundation—they cannot stand. This is why faith is the prerequisite for deeds to be accepted. The image of scattered dust emphasizes how completely worthless their actions become without the foundation of belief."
  },
  24: {
    "˹But˺ on that Day the residents of Paradise will have the best settlement": "In contrast to the disbelievers whose deeds turn to dust, the people of Paradise will have the best place to dwell. Their settlement will be filled with every comfort and blessing imaginable. While the criminals are in cramped, fiery torment, the believers are in spacious, beautiful gardens.",
    "and the finest place to rest.": "The word 'maqeel' refers to a resting place during the hottest part of the day. In Paradise, the believers will have the most pleasant, cool, comfortable place to relax. After the difficulties of the Day of Judgment, they will enjoy eternal rest and peace. This shows Allah's kindness to the believers—not only reward, but comfort and tranquility forever."
  },
  25: {
    "˹Watch for˺ the Day the heavens will burst with clouds": "On the Day of Judgment, the sky as we know it will be torn apart, and white clouds will emerge. This will be unlike any normal day—the entire structure of the universe will change. The sky splitting open is one of the terrifying signs of that Day. What seems permanent and stable to us now will be completely transformed by Allah's command.",
    "and the angels will be sent down in successive ranks.": "As the sky splits, angels will descend in rows upon rows, rank after rank. These are the angels who will carry out Allah's commands on that Day—some recording deeds, some escorting souls, some executing punishment, and some welcoming the believers. The sheer number of angels descending emphasizes the magnitude and reality of that Day. No one will be able to deny what is happening when they see this awesome sight."
  },
  26: {
    "True authority on that Day will belong ˹only˺ to the Most Compassionate.": "On the Day of Judgment, all false claims of power will vanish. Every king, president, dictator, and tyrant will be powerless. Only Allah, Ar-Rahman, will have true authority. It is significant that Allah uses His name 'Ar-Rahman' (the Most Compassionate) here—even as the Judge, He is merciful. His mercy will save the believers, and His justice will punish the wrongdoers. No one will be able to intercede without His permission, no one will speak without His leave, no one will have any power except what He grants.",
    "And it will be a hard day for the disbelievers.": "While the believers will be under Allah's mercy and shade, the disbelievers will face extreme difficulty. The length of that Day, the intensity of the heat, the terror of the events, the exposure of all their sins—everything will be unbearable for them. They will wish they could return to life and do things differently, but it will be too late. This is the consequence of rejecting Allah's guidance when it was offered to them."
  },
  27: {
    "And ˹beware of˺ the Day the wrongdoer will bite his nails ˹in regret˺": "On the Day of Judgment, the wrongdoer will be overwhelmed with such intense regret that he will bite his own hands out of anguish and frustration. This is a powerful image of someone who realizes too late that they made terrible choices. Biting one's hands is a gesture of extreme remorse—like someone who missed a life-changing opportunity and cannot forgive themselves. The wrongdoers will do this when they see the consequences of their disbelief and the rewards they missed.",
    "and say, \"Oh! I wish I had followed the Way along with the Messenger!": "In that moment of regret, the wrongdoer will cry out wishing he had walked the path of guidance alongside the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). He will realize that the messenger he rejected, mocked, or ignored was actually his only way to salvation. The \"Way\" here refers to Islam—the straight path that leads to Allah's pleasure and Paradise. But on that Day, wishes are useless. The time for following the messenger was in this worldly life, not after death."
  },
  28: {
    "Woe to me! I wish I had never taken so-and-so as a close friend.": "The wrongdoer will continue his lament, expressing deep regret over the friendships he made. 'So-and-so' (fulaan) is a placeholder for any bad companion who led him astray—it could be a friend, a leader, a peer, or anyone whose influence pushed him away from truth. This verse teaches a profound lesson: the company we keep shapes our destiny. A bad friend can lead us to Hell, while a good friend can help us reach Paradise. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"A person is upon the religion of his close friend, so let each of you look at whom he befriends.\" On Judgment Day, many will curse the friends who led them to destruction."
  },
  29: {
    "It was he who truly made me stray from the Reminder after it had reached me.\"": "The wrongdoer will blame his companion for leading him away from the Quran (the Reminder) after it had already come to him. Notice the tragedy—the guidance reached him, he had the chance to accept it, but his bad friend diverted him from it. This shows that receiving guidance is not enough; one must also protect oneself from influences that pull away from it. The truth came, but the wrong company made him reject it.",
    "And Satan has always betrayed humanity.": "Allah concludes this scene with a timeless truth: Satan always abandons those who follow him. Satan makes sins look attractive, he whispers temptations, he promises pleasure and success—but when the consequences come, he disappears. On Judgment Day, Satan will openly declare that he had no real power over people; he only invited them to evil, and they willingly followed. He will say, \"Do not blame me; blame yourselves\" (Quran 14:22). This is Satan's nature—he is a traitor who leads people to destruction and then abandons them."
  },
  30: {
    "The Messenger has cried, \"O my Lord! My people have indeed received this Quran with neglect.\"": "The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) will complain to Allah about how his own people treated the Quran. Instead of embracing it as guidance, they abandoned and neglected it. This neglect takes many forms: refusing to listen to it, refusing to believe in it, refusing to follow its commands, refusing to ponder its meanings, or refusing to live by its teachings. This verse is a warning to all Muslims—are we also guilty of neglecting the Quran? Do we read it regularly? Do we understand it? Do we implement it? The Prophet's complaint should make every believer examine their relationship with Allah's Book."
  },
  31: {
    "Similarly, We made enemies for every prophet from among the wicked": "Allah consoles the Prophet by telling him that opposition is normal for prophets. Every messenger before him faced enemies from among the criminals and evildoers of their time. Noah was opposed, Abraham was opposed, Moses was opposed, Jesus was opposed—this is the pattern. The wicked always fight against truth because truth threatens their way of life. So the Prophet should not feel discouraged; he is in noble company.",
    "but sufficient is your Lord as a Guide and Helper.": "Despite all the enemies, Allah is enough. He guides His messengers and believers to the right path, and He helps them against their opponents. The Prophet does not need large armies or great wealth to succeed; he needs Allah. And whoever has Allah's support has everything. This is deeply reassuring—when the whole world seems against you for standing for truth, remember that Allah is your Guide and Helper, and that is more than sufficient."
  },
  32: {
    "The disbelievers say, \"If only the Quran had been sent down to him all at once!\"": "The disbelievers raised another objection: why wasn't the Quran revealed all at once like the Torah was given to Moses? They thought this piecemeal revelation over 23 years was suspicious and unlike previous scriptures. This was another attempt to cast doubt on the Prophet's authenticity.",
    "˹We have sent it˺ as such ˹in stages˺ so We may reassure your heart with it.": "Allah explains the wisdom behind gradual revelation. By sending the Quran in stages, Allah strengthened the Prophet's heart. Each new revelation brought comfort, guidance, and support exactly when it was needed. When the Prophet faced a new challenge, Allah sent verses addressing it. When he was sad, consoling verses came. When guidance was needed on a specific issue, it was revealed. This ongoing connection with divine revelation kept the Prophet's faith firm and his heart reassured throughout his mission.",
    "And We have revealed it at a deliberate pace.": "The Quran was revealed slowly and distinctly, allowing time for the Prophet and the believers to understand, memorize, and implement its teachings. If it had come all at once, it would have been overwhelming. The gradual revelation allowed people to absorb its message, ask questions, and see its guidance applied to real-life situations. This method of teaching is actually more effective than dumping all information at once."
  },
  33: {
    "Whenever they bring you an argument, We come to you with the right refutation and the best explanation.": "Another benefit of gradual revelation: whenever the disbelievers came with a new objection, question, or argument, Allah would reveal verses providing the perfect response. The Quran's answers are not just adequate—they are the best possible explanations. This shows the divine origin of the Quran. A human author might struggle to answer every challenge perfectly, but Allah's responses are always complete, truthful, and superior to any human argument. This verse reassures the Prophet that he will never be left without an answer to his opponents."
  },
  34: {
    "Those who will be dragged into Hell on their faces will be in the worst place": "Despite their clever arguments in this world, the disbelievers will be dragged to Hell on their faces—the ultimate humiliation. They walked arrogantly on earth, looking down on believers, but on Judgment Day they will be dragged face-down into the Fire. Their destination, Hell, is the worst possible place—worse than any prison, any torture chamber, any suffering imaginable in this world.",
    "and are ˹now˺ farthest from the ˹Right˺ Way.": "These same people who thought they were clever and the Prophet was misguided are actually the ones most astray. They are the farthest from guidance and the closest to destruction. Their confidence in their disbelief is actually proof of how lost they are. The more they argue against truth, the deeper they sink into misguidance."
  },
  35: {
    "We certainly gave Moses the Book": "Allah begins recounting stories of destroyed nations to warn the Meccan pagans. Moses was given the Torah (the Book) as guidance for the Children of Israel. This confirms that Allah has always sent books and messengers to guide humanity. The Quran is part of this same tradition of divine revelation.",
    "and appointed his brother Aaron as his helper.": "Allah appointed Aaron (Harun) as a supporter and assistant to Moses. Moses had asked Allah for this help because he felt the mission was enormous and he wanted someone to share the burden and strengthen him. Allah granted this request. This shows that prophets worked together and that having righteous helpers is valuable. The word 'wazeer' (helper/minister) indicates someone who shares responsibility and supports the leader."
  },
  36: {
    "We had ordered ˹them˺, \"Go to the people who would deny Our signs.\"": "Allah commanded Moses and Aaron to go to Pharaoh and his people, who rejected Allah's signs and oppressed the Children of Israel. This was a difficult mission—going to the most powerful ruler on earth to demand he submit to Allah and free the slaves. But Allah's command must be obeyed regardless of how powerful the opponent seems.",
    "Then We annihilated the deniers entirely.": "After Pharaoh and his people persisted in denial despite numerous miraculous signs, Allah destroyed them completely. They were drowned in the sea while pursuing Moses and the believers. Their destruction was total—their army, their power, their arrogance—all came to nothing. This is a warning to the Quraysh: if you persist in denial like Pharaoh did, you risk a similar fate."
  },
  37: {
    "And when the people of Noah rejected the messengers": "Noah's people also rejected divine guidance. Although Noah was one messenger, rejecting him meant rejecting the message all messengers brought—the message of monotheism and obedience to Allah. When you reject one true prophet, you essentially reject all prophets because they all brought the same core message. Noah preached to his people for 950 years, but most of them refused to believe.",
    "We drowned them, making them an example to humanity.": "Allah drowned Noah's people in a great flood that covered the earth. Only those who boarded the Ark with Noah were saved. Their destruction became a lesson for all future generations. The story is known across cultures and civilizations, serving as a reminder of what happens to those who persistently reject Allah's messengers. Even today, the story of the flood warns us about the consequences of disbelief.",
    "And We have prepared a painful punishment for the wrongdoers.": "Beyond the drowning in this world, these wrongdoers will face painful punishment in the Hereafter. Their suffering did not end with death—it continues in the afterlife. This emphasizes that worldly destruction is just the beginning; eternal punishment awaits those who die in disbelief."
  },
  38: {
    "Also ˹We destroyed˺ 'Ȃd, Thamûd, and the people of the Water-pit": "Allah lists more destroyed nations: 'Aad were the people of Prophet Hud, destroyed by a violent wind that lasted for days. Thamud were the people of Prophet Salih, destroyed by a mighty blast after they killed the miraculous she-camel. The people of the Water-pit (Ar-Rass) were another community that rejected their messenger—scholars differ on exactly who they were, but they too were destroyed. Each of these nations was powerful and prosperous, yet none could escape Allah's punishment when they persisted in denial.",
    "as well as many peoples in between.": "Between these famous nations were countless other communities who also received messengers and rejected them. History is filled with destroyed civilizations, many of whom are forgotten. The Quran does not name them all, but indicates that the pattern repeated itself many times. This shows that rejection of truth and subsequent destruction is not rare—it is a recurring theme in human history."
  },
  39: {
    "For each We set forth ˹various˺ lessons": "Allah gave every nation clear examples, parables, and lessons. They were not destroyed without warning. Each community received guidance, signs, and reminders. Prophets explained the truth to them using various methods. They had every opportunity to understand and accept. Their destruction came only after they had been thoroughly warned and given every chance.",
    "and We ultimately destroyed each.": "Despite all the warnings and lessons, when they persisted in rejection, Allah destroyed them completely. 'Tatbeera' means utter destruction—not partial defeat, but complete annihilation of their power and civilization. Their magnificent buildings, their advanced societies, their wealth—all became ruins. This is the fate of all who stubbornly reject Allah's guidance after it has been made clear to them."
  },
  40: {
    "They have certainly passed by the city ˹of Sodom˺, which had been showered with a dreadful rain ˹of stones˺.": "The Meccan traders regularly traveled past the ruins of Sodom and Gomorrah on their trade routes to Syria. These cities were destroyed because of the sins of the people of Prophet Lot—they were showered with stones of baked clay that rained down from the sky. The area near the Dead Sea still bears witness to this destruction. The Meccans saw these ruins with their own eyes during their travels.",
    "Have they not seen its ruins?": "Allah asks: did they not see the evidence of destruction right before their eyes? The ruins were a visible sign, a physical reminder of what happens to nations that reject Allah's messengers and persist in sin. The evidence was not hidden or ancient legend—it was tangible and present on their regular routes.",
    "But they do not expect to be resurrected.": "The reason they did not learn from these ruins is that they did not believe in resurrection. Since they denied the Day of Judgment, they thought death was the end. So what lesson could ruins teach them? In their minds, those ancient people simply died—no ongoing punishment, no accountability. This denial of the afterlife prevented them from taking the warning seriously."
  },
  41: {
    "When they see you ˹O Prophet˺, they only make fun of you": "Instead of respecting the Prophet or considering his message, the disbelievers mocked him whenever they saw him. Their arrogance prevented them from taking him seriously. They looked at his simple appearance, his lack of worldly power, and made him an object of ridicule. This was painful for the Prophet, but it was also a test of his patience.",
    "˹saying,˺ \"Is this the one that Allah has sent as a messenger?": "They said this sarcastically, as if to say: \"This ordinary man is supposed to be God's messenger? How ridiculous!\" They expected a messenger to be wealthy, powerful, accompanied by angels, or displaying constant miracles. A man who walked in marketplaces and ate food like everyone else did not fit their expectations. Their criteria for prophethood were based on worldly standards, not divine wisdom."
  },
  42: {
    "He would have almost tricked us away from our gods, had we not been so devoted to them.\"": "The pagans admitted that the Prophet's message was so compelling that he almost convinced them to abandon their idols. They felt the power of his words and the truth of his arguments. But instead of accepting the truth, they viewed their stubborn attachment to idols as loyalty and patience. They congratulated themselves for \"holding firm\" against the Prophet's persuasion. How twisted! They saw rejecting truth as a virtue.",
    "˹But˺ soon they will know, when they face the punishment, who is far astray from the ˹Right˺ Way.": "Allah warns that they will soon discover the truth—when punishment comes to them, whether in this world or the next. At that moment, it will become absolutely clear who was truly misguided. They mocked the Prophet as lost, but the reality will be exposed: they were the ones wandering far from the right path. By then, however, it will be too late for them."
  },
  43: {
    "Have you seen ˹O Prophet˺ the one who has taken their own desires as their god?": "Allah draws attention to a particular type of person: one who makes their own desires and whims the ultimate authority in their life. Whatever they feel like doing, they do. Whatever their ego wants, they pursue. Their desires become their god because they worship and obey these desires the way a believer worships and obeys Allah. This is a form of shirk (polytheism)—making something other than Allah the ultimate guide for one's life.",
    "Will you then be a keeper over them?": "Allah asks the Prophet: can you force such people to believe? Can you control their hearts? The answer is no. The Prophet's job is to deliver the message, not to compel belief. People who have made their desires their god are so enslaved to themselves that no amount of reasoning reaches them. The Prophet is not responsible for their choices—he has fulfilled his duty by warning them."
  },
  44: {
    "Or do you think that most of them listen or understand?": "Allah asks rhetorically: does the Prophet think these people actually hear and comprehend the message? They have ears but do not truly listen; they have minds but do not truly reflect. They hear the Quran but block its meaning from entering their hearts. Understanding requires willingness to accept truth, which they lack.",
    "They are only like cattle—no, more than that, they are astray from the ˹Right˺ Way!": "Allah compares them to cattle—animals that eat, drink, and follow their instincts without deeper thought or purpose. But then Allah says they are actually worse than cattle. Why? Because cattle fulfill their purpose; they do not have the ability to reason or choose guidance. But these people have been given intelligence and free will, yet they choose to ignore guidance. They are lower than animals because they waste the gifts Allah gave them. Animals are not accountable, but these humans will be."
  },
  45: {
    "Have you not seen how your Lord extends the shade": "Allah directs our attention to a daily phenomenon we often take for granted: the shade. In the morning, shadows are long; as the sun rises, they shorten; in the evening, they lengthen again. This extension and movement of shade is a sign of Allah's control over creation. The shade provides relief from heat and light, a mercy from Allah that we experience every day.",
    "—He could have simply made it ˹remain˺ still if He so willed—": "If Allah wanted, the shade could be permanent and unchanging. There could be endless night or endless day, permanent shadow or constant blazing sun. But Allah, in His wisdom, made shade dynamic—it moves and changes. This alternation is a blessing that makes life possible and comfortable. Fixed conditions would make life unbearable.",
    "then We make the sun its guide": "The sun \"guides\" the shade by its movement across the sky. The shade's position and length depend on where the sun is. This connection between sun and shade shows how Allah coordinates His creation perfectly. Everything in the universe works in harmony according to His design."
  },
  46: {
    "causing the shade to retreat gradually?": "As the sun moves, the shade is gradually \"pulled back\" or shortened. This happens so smoothly and slowly that we barely notice it. Allah could have made shade disappear instantly, but He does it gently, gradually. This gradual change is a mercy—sudden changes would be jarring and uncomfortable. The smoothness of natural transitions reflects Allah's gentleness in managing His creation."
  },
  47: {
    "He is the One Who has made the night for you as a cover": "Allah made the night like a garment that covers you. Just as clothes cover and protect your body, the darkness of night covers the earth, bringing rest and privacy. The night conceals, calms, and cools after the heat of the day. This comparison to clothing shows how the night wraps around us protectively.",
    "and ˹made˺ sleep for resting": "Allah created sleep as a means of rest for our bodies and minds. During sleep, the body repairs itself, the mind processes experiences, and energy is restored. Without sleep, humans cannot function. Sleep is a sign of Allah's mercy—He did not create us to work endlessly but built rest into our very nature.",
    "and the day for rising.": "After the rest of night, the day comes for activity, work, and seeking provision. The word 'nushoor' (rising/resurrection) also hints at the final resurrection—just as we \"die\" each night in sleep and are \"resurrected\" each morning, we will one day be resurrected after death. The daily cycle of sleep and waking is a reminder of death and resurrection."
  },
  48: {
    "And He is the One Who sends the winds ushering in His mercy": "Allah sends winds before the rain as good news. When people feel the cool wind and see clouds gathering, they know rain is coming. The wind is described as a herald announcing Allah's mercy (rain). This shows Allah's kindness—He does not send rain suddenly without warning but prepares people for it with the pleasant arrival of wind.",
    "and We send down pure rain from the sky": "The rain that falls is pure and purifying. It is clean water, free from contamination, suitable for drinking, washing, and purification for worship. This pure water comes from the sky, transformed from salty ocean water through a cycle that Allah designed. No human could create this system of purification on such a massive scale."
  },
  49: {
    "giving life to a lifeless land": "Rain brings dead, barren land back to life. Where there was only dry, cracked earth, suddenly plants sprout, flowers bloom, and greenery appears. This revival of dead land is a powerful sign pointing to resurrection. The One who can bring dead land to life can certainly bring dead humans back to life. Every spring season is a reminder of the resurrection to come.",
    "and providing water for countless animals and humans of Our Own creation.": "The rain does not just revive land—it provides drinking water for all living creatures. Animals, from the smallest insect to the largest elephant, depend on this water. Humans build their civilizations around water sources. Without rain, life as we know it would be impossible. This shows Allah's care for all His creatures, providing for their needs through the simple yet miraculous process of rainfall."
  },
  50: {
    "We certainly disperse it among them so they may be mindful": "Allah distributes rain across different lands at different times. Sometimes one region receives abundant rain while another experiences drought; then the situation reverses. This distribution is meant to make people reflect and remember Allah. When rain comes after drought, grateful people recognize Allah's blessing. When rain is withheld, thoughtful people turn to Allah in prayer. The variation is meant to keep people conscious of their dependence on Allah.",
    "but most people persist in ungratefulness.": "Despite these clear signs and blessings, most people remain ungrateful. They take rain for granted when it comes and complain when it doesn't. They forget that every drop is a gift from Allah. They use the water without thanking the One who provided it. This ingratitude is one of humanity's greatest failings—receiving countless blessings yet failing to acknowledge and thank the Giver."
  },
  51: {
    "Had We willed, We could have easily sent a warner to every society.": "Allah could have sent a separate prophet to every town and village simultaneously. He has the power to do so. But in His wisdom, He chose to send one final messenger for all of humanity. This unified message brings people together rather than dividing them into separate communities with separate prophets. Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is the messenger for the entire world, uniting all believers under one guidance."
  },
  52: {
    "So do not yield to the disbelievers": "Since the Prophet carries this immense responsibility as the messenger to all humanity, he must remain firm. He should not give in to the demands of disbelievers—whether their demands for compromise, their pressures to soften the message, or their attempts to discourage him. Yielding to them would be a betrayal of his mission.",
    "but strive diligently against them with this ˹Quran˺.": "The weapon for this struggle is the Quran itself. The Prophet is commanded to make great jihad (strenuous effort) against disbelief using the Quran. This means arguing with its proofs, calling people with its message, refuting falsehood with its truth, and transforming society through its guidance. The Quran is the greatest tool for changing hearts and minds. This \"great jihad\" is an intellectual and spiritual struggle, using the power of divine words to combat ignorance and disbelief."
  },
  53: {
    "And He is the One Who merges the two bodies of water: one fresh and palatable and the other salty and bitter": "Allah has created two types of water bodies: fresh water (rivers, lakes, springs) that is sweet and pleasant to drink, and salt water (seas, oceans) that is salty and bitter. Both exist on the same planet, and in some places they meet—like where rivers flow into oceans or where underground fresh water meets sea water.",
    "placing between them a barrier they cannot cross.": "Despite meeting, these two types of water do not mix completely. Allah has placed an invisible barrier between them. This has been confirmed by modern science, which discovered that where fresh and salt water meet, there is a zone with different properties that prevents immediate mixing. This \"barrier\" (barzakh) was unknown to humans at the time of revelation, yet the Quran described it accurately. This is a miracle of the Quran and a sign of Allah's precise control over creation. Fresh water remains available for drinking despite being surrounded by vast salty oceans—a mercy and a sign for those who reflect."
  },
  54: {
    "And He is the One Who creates human beings from a ˹humble˺ liquid": "Allah created humans from a drop of fluid—the reproductive fluid that seems insignificant and humble. From this tiny, despised liquid, Allah fashions complete human beings with bones, flesh, organs, intellect, and souls. This is a profound reminder of our humble origins. No matter how proud or arrogant a person becomes, they should remember they came from a drop of fluid. This also demonstrates Allah's incredible power—to create something so complex and magnificent from something so simple.",
    "then establishes for them bonds of kinship and marriage": "From this creation, Allah established two types of relationships that form the foundation of human society: kinship (nasab)—the blood relationships through birth such as parents, children, siblings, and extended family; and marriage (sihr)—the relationships through union such as spouses and in-laws. These bonds create families, communities, and civilizations. They provide love, support, identity, and continuity across generations. Islam places great emphasis on maintaining these ties.",
    "For your Lord is Most Capable.": "Allah is able to do all things. Creating humans from fluid, establishing complex social bonds, and managing all of creation is easy for Him. Nothing is difficult for Allah. This phrase reminds us that the One who created us from nothing can certainly resurrect us, guide us, and provide for us. His capability is unlimited."
  },
  55: {
    "Yet they worship besides Allah what can neither benefit nor harm them.": "Despite all the signs of Allah's power and mercy described in previous verses, the polytheists still worship idols and false gods that have no power whatsoever. These objects cannot grant any benefit—no provision, no protection, no guidance, no answered prayers. Nor can they cause any harm—they cannot punish those who ignore them or defend themselves when attacked. They are completely powerless. How irrational to worship something weaker than yourself!",
    "And the disbeliever always collaborates against their Lord.": "The disbeliever acts as a helper and supporter of Satan against Allah. By rejecting Allah's guidance and following falsehood, they essentially side with the enemies of truth. Instead of using the faculties Allah gave them to worship Him, they use them to oppose His religion, support false ideologies, and fight against His messengers. This is the ultimate betrayal—using Allah's gifts to rebel against Him."
  },
  56: {
    "And We have sent you ˹O Prophet˺ only as a deliverer of good news and a warner.": "Allah clarifies the Prophet's role: he is a bearer of good news for those who believe (promising them Paradise and Allah's pleasure) and a warner for those who disbelieve (alerting them to punishment and Allah's wrath). He is not sent to force people to believe, to control their hearts, or to perform miracles on demand. His job is to convey the message clearly and completely. The response of people is their own responsibility. This defined role should give the Prophet peace of mind—he has fulfilled his duty by delivering the message."
  },
  57: {
    "Say, \"I do not ask you for any reward for this ˹message˺": "The Prophet is commanded to make clear that he seeks no personal gain from his mission. He does not want their money, their power, their praise, or any worldly benefit. This is crucial evidence of his sincerity. Throughout history, false prophets and cult leaders have exploited their followers for wealth and power. But the true Prophet lived in poverty despite having the opportunity to be wealthy, proving his message was genuinely from Allah, not for personal gain.",
    "but whoever wishes, let them pursue the Way to their Lord.\"": "The only thing the Prophet asks is that people take a path to their Lord—meaning accept guidance, follow the truth, and work toward their own salvation. This is not really a request for himself; it is an invitation for their own benefit. The Prophet gains nothing if people believe; rather, the believers themselves gain everything. This shows the Prophet's selfless concern for humanity's wellbeing."
  },
  58: {
    "Put your trust in the Ever-Living, Who never dies": "Allah commands the Prophet to rely completely on Him. Unlike human allies who may die, abandon you, or prove unreliable, Allah is the Ever-Living (Al-Hayy) who never dies. He is always there, always capable, always aware. When you trust in humans, they may fail you—they may pass away, change their minds, or lack the ability to help. But trusting in Allah means relying on One who is eternal and whose support never ends.",
    "and glorify His praises.": "Along with trust, the Prophet is commanded to glorify and praise Allah constantly. This combination of trust (tawakkul) and praise (tasbih) is the formula for a peaceful heart. When you trust Allah and remember His perfection and blessings, anxiety and fear diminish. Glorifying Allah also keeps the heart connected to Him and prevents arrogance or forgetfulness.",
    "Sufficient is He as All-Aware of the sins of His servants.": "Allah knows every sin committed by every person. Nothing is hidden from Him. This is both a warning and a comfort. For the disbelievers, it means their crimes are recorded and they will be held accountable. For the Prophet, it means he does not need to worry about exposing or punishing the wrongdoers himself—Allah sees everything and will deal with them accordingly. The Prophet's job is to warn; Allah's job is to judge."
  },
  59: {
    "˹He is˺ the One Who created the heavens and the earth and everything in between in six Days": "This Ever-Living God whom you should trust is the Creator of the entire universe. The heavens (all the celestial bodies and realms above), the earth, and everything between them were created in six days. These \"days\" are periods of time known to Allah, not necessarily 24-hour human days. The point is that Allah created this vast, complex universe with deliberate planning and stages, demonstrating His power and wisdom.",
    "then established Himself on the Throne.": "After creation, Allah rose over His Throne (Arsh) in a manner befitting His majesty. We believe in this as Allah described it without trying to imagine how it is, because nothing is like Allah. The Throne is the greatest of Allah's creations, and His establishment over it signifies His sovereignty and control over all creation. He rules the universe from His Throne, managing every affair.",
    "˹He is˺ the Most Compassionate!": "Despite His immense power and majesty, He is Ar-Rahman—the Most Compassionate. His mercy encompasses all creation. This combination of power and mercy is comforting: the One ruling the universe is not cruel or indifferent but deeply merciful. His decisions and decrees come from compassion.",
    "Ask ˹none other than˺ the All-Knowledgeable about Himself.": "If you want to know about Allah—His attributes, His nature, His actions—ask Him or refer to what He has revealed. Do not speculate or invent ideas about Allah. Only Allah truly knows Himself, and He has taught us about Himself through the Quran and the Prophet. Any knowledge about Allah must come from these authentic sources, not from human imagination or philosophy."
  },
  60: {
    "When it is said to them, \"Prostrate to the Most Compassionate,\"": "When the believers call the pagans to prostrate to Allah, using His beautiful name Ar-Rahman (The Most Compassionate), they should be attracted to such a merciful God. Prostration (sujood) is the ultimate act of humility and submission to Allah, where the highest part of the body (the face) is placed on the ground before the Creator.",
    "they ask ˹in disgust˺, \"What is 'the Most Compassionate'?": "Instead of responding to the beautiful meaning of this name, they pretend not to know it or mock it. They say \"What is Ar-Rahman?\" as if it were a foreign or meaningless term. In reality, Ar-Rahman was known to the Arabs, but their arrogance made them reject anything associated with the Prophet's message. This is a tactic of deniers throughout history—dismissing or mocking sacred terms rather than engaging with their meaning.",
    "Will we prostrate to whatever you order us to?\"": "They arrogantly refuse to prostrate simply because the Prophet commands it. Their pride prevents them from submitting. They essentially say: \"We won't bow down just because you tell us to.\" This reveals that their problem is not intellectual doubt but stubborn pride. They refuse to humble themselves before Allah or accept guidance from His messenger.",
    "And it only drives them farther away.": "This invitation to worship, rather than bringing them closer to Allah, pushes them further into rejection. When hearts are diseased with arrogance, even beautiful invitations to mercy are met with hostility. Every call to guidance increases their aversion. This is a tragic state—the medicine that should cure them actually makes them sicker because they refuse to take it properly."
  },
  61: {
    "Blessed is the One Who has placed constellations in the sky": "Allah, full of blessings and majesty, has decorated the sky with constellations (buruj)—groups of stars that form patterns and serve as markers for navigation and seasons. Ancient travelers used these constellations to find their way across deserts and seas. The night sky is like a beautiful ceiling adorned with lights, pointing to a magnificent Creator.",
    "as well as a ˹radiant˺ lamp": "The sun is described as a lamp (siraj) because it produces its own light and heat, illuminating the day and enabling life on earth. Without the sun's light, there would be no vision, no growth, no warmth. It is perfectly positioned—close enough to warm us but far enough not to burn us. This precise placement is evidence of deliberate design.",
    "and a luminous moon.": "The moon is described as luminous (munir)—it reflects light rather than producing its own. It illuminates the night with a gentle glow, different from the intense brightness of the sun. The moon's phases provide a natural calendar, and its light has guided travelers and inspired poets throughout human history. Both the sun and moon are signs of Allah's creative power and wisdom."
  },
  62: {
    "And He is the One Who causes the day and the night to alternate": "Allah makes day and night follow each other in a continuous cycle. When day ends, night comes; when night ends, day returns. This alternation is so regular that we can predict sunrise and sunset times precisely. This predictable pattern allows humans to plan their lives, work during the day, and rest at night.",
    "˹as a sign˺ for whoever desires to be mindful or to be grateful.": "This alternation of day and night is a sign for two types of people: those who want to reflect and remember (yadhdhakkar) and those who want to be grateful (shakoor). A reflective person sees the cycle and thinks about the Creator who designed it. A grateful person appreciates the blessings of daylight for work and nighttime for rest. If someone misses an opportunity to worship or reflect during the day, the night offers another chance; if they miss the night, the day returns. Allah provides continuous opportunities for those who seek them."
  },
  63: {
    "The ˹true˺ servants of the Most Compassionate are those who walk on the earth humbly": "Allah begins describing the special qualities of His true servants. First, they walk with humility—not arrogantly strutting or showing off, but with modesty and dignity. Their walk reflects their inner state: they do not consider themselves superior to others. They are aware that the earth they walk on belongs to Allah and that they themselves are merely servants. Humility in walking represents humility in all aspects of life.",
    "and when the foolish address them ˹improperly˺, they only respond with peace.": "When ignorant people insult them, provoke them, or speak foolishly to them, they do not respond with anger or retaliation. Instead, they respond with words of peace—either saying \"Salam\" (peace) or speaking in a peaceful, dignified manner that does not escalate conflict. They do not lower themselves to the level of the ignorant. This requires tremendous self-control and reflects inner peace and confidence. They know that arguing with fools is pointless and that their dignity comes from Allah, not from winning arguments."
  },
  64: {
    "˹They are˺ those who spend ˹a good portion of˺ the night, prostrating themselves and standing before their Lord.": "The servants of Ar-Rahman are not only humble in public but also devoted in private. They spend parts of the night in prayer—prostrating (sujood) and standing (qiyam) before Allah when others are sleeping. Night prayer (tahajjud) is one of the most beloved acts of worship because it is done in secret, purely for Allah's sake, with no one watching. It shows true sincerity and love for Allah. While the world sleeps, they are in conversation with their Lord, seeking His pleasure and forgiveness."
  },
  65: {
    "˹They are˺ those who pray, \"Our Lord! Keep the punishment of Hell away from us": "Despite their worship and humility, the servants of Ar-Rahman do not feel safe from Allah's punishment. They do not assume they are guaranteed Paradise. Instead, they constantly pray to be saved from Hell. This shows healthy fear—they never take their salvation for granted. Even the most righteous should worry about their standing with Allah and continue to seek His protection.",
    "for its punishment is indeed unrelenting.": "They understand that Hell's punishment is continuous and inescapable for its inhabitants. It does not diminish, pause, or end. It clings to its people like a debt that can never be paid off. This understanding motivates their prayers and their righteous actions. They do not want to risk such a permanent, severe consequence."
  },
  66: {
    "It is certainly an evil place to settle and reside.\"": "They acknowledge that Hell is the worst possible destination. It is evil as a temporary stop and even worse as a permanent residence. There is no comfort, no rest, no relief in Hell. Every aspect of it is suffering. By declaring this in their prayers, the servants of Ar-Rahman show their awareness and their desperate desire to avoid such a fate. This fear keeps them motivated to worship and avoid sins."
  },
  67: {
    "˹They are˺ those who spend neither wastefully nor stingily, but moderately in between.": "The servants of Ar-Rahman are balanced in their spending. They do not waste money on extravagance, luxury, or unnecessary things (israf). At the same time, they are not miserly, depriving themselves or their families of necessities (taqtir). They follow a middle path—spending appropriately, meeting needs, being generous without being foolish, and being careful without being greedy. This balance applies to spending on themselves, their families, and charity. Islam teaches moderation in all things, and financial management is a key area where this principle applies. A person's spending habits reflect their character and priorities."
  },
  68: {
    "˹They are˺ those who do not invoke any other god besides Allah": "The first and greatest quality is pure monotheism (tawhid). The servants of Ar-Rahman worship Allah alone without associating partners with Him. They do not pray to idols, saints, graves, or any other being. Their devotion is exclusively for Allah. This is the foundation of faith—without it, no other good deed is accepted.",
    "nor take a ˹human˺ life—made sacred by Allah—except with ˹legal˺ right": "They respect the sanctity of human life. They do not murder, kill innocents, or take life unjustly. The only exception is through legal means established by Islamic law—such as judicial punishment for capital crimes carried out by proper authorities, or legitimate self-defense. Human life is sacred in Islam, and taking it without right is among the greatest sins.",
    "nor commit fornication.": "They avoid sexual relations outside of marriage (zina). This includes both adultery and fornication. Such acts destroy families, spread diseases, create confusion about lineage, and corrupt society. The servants of Ar-Rahman guard their chastity and fulfill their desires only through lawful marriage.",
    "And whoever does ˹any of˺ this will face the penalty.": "Allah warns that committing any of these three major sins—shirk, murder, or fornication—will result in severe punishment. This is not a minor matter. These sins carry heavy consequences both in this world and the next. The believer must avoid them completely."
  },
  69: {
    "Their punishment will be multiplied on the Day of Judgment": "Those who commit these major sins and die without repentance will face double or multiplied punishment. The severity is increased because of the enormity of the sins. Each of these three sins is a great crime against Allah's rights, human rights, or both.",
    "and they will remain in it forever, in disgrace.": "They will abide in this punishment eternally, humiliated and disgraced. They will not find any honor or relief. This eternal nature applies to those who die as disbelievers (committing shirk). For believers who commit murder or fornication without repentance, scholars discuss whether \"forever\" means a very long time or eternal, based on other verses about Allah's forgiveness. The key message is the extreme seriousness of these sins."
  },
  70: {
    "As for those who repent, believe, and do good deeds": "The door of repentance is always open. Even if someone committed shirk, murder, or fornication, sincere repentance can save them. Repentance requires feeling genuine regret, stopping the sin, resolving never to return to it, and following up with faith and righteous deeds. All three components are necessary—repentance alone is not enough without faith, and faith alone is not enough without good deeds that demonstrate transformation.",
    "they are the ones whose evil deeds Allah will change into good deeds.": "This is an amazing gift of Allah's mercy: not only does He forgive the sins of those who truly repent, but He actually converts their evil deeds into good deeds on their record. Some scholars explain this means the sins are erased and replaced with rewards. Others explain that the bad habits and tendencies are transformed into good ones—the person who used to commit fornication now becomes chaste, the one who worshipped idols now worships Allah alone. Either way, it shows Allah's incredible generosity to those who turn back to Him.",
    "For Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah's forgiveness and mercy are emphasized again. No matter how great the sins, His forgiveness is greater. No matter how much someone has strayed, His mercy can embrace them if they return sincerely. This gives hope to every sinner: it is never too late to repent."
  },
  71: {
    "And whoever repents and does good has truly turned to Allah properly.": "This verse confirms that genuine repentance combined with righteous action is a true return to Allah. It is not just words or feelings—it is a complete transformation demonstrated by changed behavior. When someone repents properly (matab), they have made their way back to Allah successfully. This phrase provides reassurance: if you repent and do good, your repentance has been accepted, and you are on the right path."
  },
  72: {
    "˹They are˺ those who do not bear false witness": "The servants of Ar-Rahman do not give false testimony. They do not lie in courts, do not falsely accuse others, and do not distort truth for personal benefit. False witness can destroy innocent people's lives, wealth, and reputations. It corrupts justice and spreads evil in society. Additionally, this can mean they do not attend gatherings of falsehood—events involving sin, mockery of religion, or useless activities.",
    "and when they come across falsehood, they pass ˹it˺ by with dignity.": "When they encounter vain, sinful, or useless speech and activities (laghw), they do not participate or linger. They pass by with dignity, maintaining their honor without engaging. They do not mock, argue, or involve themselves in what does not benefit them. This shows their wisdom and self-respect. A dignified believer does not waste time on foolishness or get dragged into pointless disputes."
  },
  73: {
    "˹They are˺ those who, when reminded of the revelation of their Lord, do not turn a blind eye or a deaf ear to it.": "When the verses of Allah are recited to the servants of Ar-Rahman, they respond properly. They do not fall upon the verses deaf and blind—meaning they do not ignore them, dismiss them, or fail to understand them. Instead, they listen attentively, reflect deeply, and act upon what they hear. They open their ears, eyes, and hearts to Allah's guidance. This contrasts sharply with disbelievers who hear the Quran but do not benefit from it because they approach it with closed hearts. The servants of Ar-Rahman approach Allah's words with humility, eagerness, and readiness to obey."
  },
  74: {
    "˹They are˺ those who pray, \"Our Lord! Bless us with ˹pious˺ spouses and offspring who will be the joy of our hearts": "The servants of Ar-Rahman care about their families' spiritual state. They pray for spouses and children who are righteous, who bring them joy by their faith and good character. \"Joy of the eyes\" (qurrata a'yun) is an Arabic expression meaning something that brings deep happiness and contentment when you see it. They want to look at their families and feel joy because they see them praying, reciting Quran, and living righteously. This dua reflects understanding that a righteous family is one of life's greatest blessings.",
    "and make us models for the righteous.\"": "They also ask Allah to make them leaders (imams) for the righteous. This is not about seeking power or fame but about being exemplary Muslims whose lives inspire others toward piety. They want to be role models in worship, character, and conduct. They want to leave a legacy of guidance. This dua shows high ambition in faith—not just to be saved themselves but to guide others to salvation as well."
  },
  75: {
    "It is they who will be rewarded with ˹elevated˺ mansions ˹in Paradise˺ for their perseverance": "After describing all these beautiful qualities, Allah reveals the reward: elevated chambers or mansions (ghuraf) in Paradise—the highest and most honored places. These are not ordinary dwellings but special residences for special servants. The reason given is their patience (sabr)—patience in obeying Allah, patience in avoiding sins, patience in facing hardships and tests. All the qualities mentioned required patience: being humble when provoked, praying at night when tired, avoiding sins when tempted, spending moderately when desires push for more.",
    "and will be received with salutations and ˹greetings of˺ peace": "When they enter these mansions, they will be welcomed with greetings of peace and honor. Angels will greet them, and they will greet each other with \"Salam.\" This is the opposite of the humiliation promised to the disbelievers. The servants of Ar-Rahman will experience honor, dignity, and peaceful welcome in their eternal home."
  },
  76: {
    "staying there forever.": "Their stay in these beautiful mansions is eternal. Unlike worldly homes that decay or must be left behind at death, Paradise is forever. They will never be evicted, never need to move, never experience the joy ending.",
    "What an excellent place to settle and reside!": "This is the exact opposite of how Hell was described (\"an evil place to settle and reside\" in verse 66). Paradise is praised as the most excellent settlement and residence. Everything about it is perfect—its beauty, its peace, its provisions, and its eternity. This contrast between the destinations of believers and disbelievers is meant to motivate the reader: which destination do you want? Your choices today determine where you end up."
  },
  77: {
    "Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ \"You ˹all˺ would not ˹even˺ matter to my Lord were it not for your faith ˹in Him˺.": "The Prophet is commanded to deliver a powerful truth: without worship and faith, humans have no value before Allah. Allah does not need our worship—He is not increased by our obedience or decreased by our disobedience. We are the ones who need Him. If people do not worship Allah, they lose their purpose and worth. It is faith and worship that elevate humans above other creatures. Without these, humans are just another species—actually worse, as stated earlier, because they rejected guidance that animals were never offered.",
    "But now you ˹disbelievers˺ have denied ˹the truth˺, so the torment is bound to come.\"": "The surah ends with a stern warning to the disbelievers: you have rejected the truth, and now punishment is inevitable. The word \"lizaam\" means something that will cling to them, attach to them, become inseparable from them. They have made their choice, and the consequences will come. This is the final warning of Surah Al-Furqan—a chapter that began by praising Allah who sent the Criterion and ends by reminding humanity that their value lies in their faith and that rejection of truth leads to inescapable punishment."
  }
};